segments.text: Did anybody give you any advice what you would claim or not claim on your expense account?
Well, you mentioned Perdim.
I believe we pretty well actually gave.
We had to have receipts.
As I recall, we had to have actual expenses.
You didn't claim just $8, $20 worth today.
You had to submit receipts for most everything.
And that's the way, I don't even remember if we had per diem versus just, it was a maximum, I'm sure it was a maximum.
But did anybody make it clear you couldn't claim beer?
Oh, yeah, yeah, no, you couldn't claim those kinds.
No drinks, yeah, right.
Or parking was a problem.
In those early days, how often did a graduate student go along?
Oh, well, it wasn't infrequent.
I remember Ed Smith and I going to the Valley,
to do research on grapefruit, and another guy and I going to West Texas.
Graduate students were pretty well integrated into the research process.
Yeah, we used them frequently.
And there used to be a lot more original data gathering.
I don't know of anybody now
who goes out and does field survey work.
I can't think of anybody doing that now.
Whereas then it was common, particularly in the summertime.
That's what you spent your summers doing.
You were surveying households or you were surveying farmers.
Describe that.
That's important.
Well, you actually went out and did a survey like you did house to house schedules.
If you're doing dairy consumption, you would go to Stephenville or someplace and take a survey.
You know, dear madam, may I interview you?
I've got this questionnaire.
How much milk do you
buy in a week and how do you use it and blah blah blah.
Primary data right from the consumer.
Now most of our data comes from secondary sources.
How would you have selected, in such a survey, how would you have selected this town instead of some other town?

depending on what the study was, but you'd try to find a representative quote-unquote town, and then within that town, you'd do a sample, either from the phone book or the city directory or something.
You could do a sample or a stratified sample, so it supposedly was representative.
But you actually went door-to-door.
And the same thing with producers, farmers.
Like up in some county in, you know, West Texas or wherever, they would do a sample of farmers to find out what their production practices were, and you went head-to-head with the farmer.
Do you remember any interesting...
Response you got from a on a survey conversation No, people were pretty cooperative.

I don't know producer told you it was none of your business I Didn't because I wasn't doing production Surveys, but I can remember getting that response from marketing firms I mean sometimes they'd like to get told you the guy about ran me out of his office and
Or they simply said, we're not interested in cooperating.
That's our business, not yours.
And so you just left those people alone.
When you or someone was doing that, from what institution or what organization did you all identify yourself as being?
What did you say you were from?
Well, we'd be from the Texas Agricultural Experiment Station, was who was funding that research.
And then we had some kind of ID, I don't know, a card or a letter,
How soon did you mention Texas A&M?
Oh, right up front, first thing.
And what was their reaction?
Usually very favorable.
Yeah, if A&M had a good image, yeah.
And did anybody before you went out suggest how you should dress?
Well, we sort of, yeah.
Yes, that was made clear, if you didn't understand it, that you dressed very professionally, and probably with a tie on, depending on the time.
Even in the summer, I suppose you'd have a tie on.
Probably a name tag that would identify you.
How soon after you arrived here did you have some results of some of that field work that made you feel good?
Published or paper or read or something or other?
Well, within a, I know with, let's see, I believe it was the first summer I was here, we did a big foray to the valley to work on marketing orders.
And we used to publish what are called departmental reports.
And then generally, hopefully, those would evolve into a journal article.
So I believe by that fall, I had something worked up.
We had a good experience in the valley with the fruits and vegetable people.
And I believe I had something worked up on carrots.
Maybe it took as long as a year.
The pressure wasn't as great then to get things, get them out.
And of course, it wasn't as fast either.
They didn't have computers.
It was six copies of everything if you wanted to copy something with carbons and so on.
But things moved slower.
Everybody moves more slowly in terms of getting things published.
It took longer.
And so I would say within a, I think I got satisfaction probably within the first six months or so in terms of, yeah, this is probably worthwhile, what we're doing here.
And when did you first do something that Ty Tim or somebody in a position of responsibility
patted you on the back, or maybe in the pocketbook too.

Well, that would have been the trip to the valley where we met with the powers that be down there, mostly big producers and some of the marketing people, the packers, and talked to them about their situation as far as the marketing orders went and how important they were.
I remember we had a big meeting at some big motel in McAllen

and it was well attended and we put on a slide show and so on and I got the impression that they were I was told that we did a good job and they were favorably impressed and that sort of was a good launching pad but it was it was a it was a dog and pony show is what it was it wasn't a professional session or anything and at the end of that first semester do you remember any kind of evaluation or no no well
I say no, but I'm not sure.
It seems like forever we passed out these sheets, one through ten, where people rated you on about 18 things, but I don't know if they ever went to anybody.
You just passed them out for your own amusement, and it wasn't until many, many years later that they started actual formal evaluations where they went with your packet to be reviewed by the head.
Did Dr. Tim in the early years...
Did he ever call you in and give you an evaluation, tell you what you were doing well or not so well?
Yeah, I believe he did that about once a year.
He'd have a session that kind of told you what they thought was going on.
I remember McNeely called me in one time, and I had begun to work with Marshall Godwin came in from Florida.
He was a hot item, and we'd set up a little...
camp down in the corner of the building, Lonnie Jones and Marshall Goddard and myself and somebody else, and he was going to lead us into big things in marketing.
But we weren't moving very fast.
I remember McNeely called me in and kind of chewed on me once, which was good for me because I should have had that from the start, that we're not getting enough done here and so on and so forth.
And so that was a good reprimand.
Not reprimand so much as encouragement, I guess you'd say.
Describe this man, Ty Tim.
Ty Tim from Hallisville, Texas, raised by his aunts, as I recall, a kind of a bear of a man, very gregarious, garrulous, hail-hardy, well-met fellow.
all smiling all the time.
And I've heard Ty say, I'll take care of you right after I take care of myself.
Only half in jest, I think.
Everybody, I think, loved Ty.
At least you liked Ty, whether you liked what he was doing.
He got his doctorate of public administration at Harvard, which I think he always kind of felt slightly second class because he didn't have a PhD.
But he wanted you to know that he had this degree from Harvard
Maybe he even had a master's of public administration from Harvard.
But he was an operator.
I know when I first got here the first summer, I got to teach ag policy to a bunch of guys who were older than I was.
I was 28 years old.
No, 29 at that time.
And because Ty wanted to go to Colorado, where it was cool.
And he did.
And I did.
But he would take care of you.
He took care of you.
And then he got in this deal in the Common Market, so he went to Europe.
I don't know how many times he went to Europe on this Common Market operation, but he was a good friend of Earl Rudder.
I'm not sure what class.
I think President Rudder was younger than Ty was.
They were both in the 30s someplace, class of 30-something.
And Lupo was a good friend of Ty's, and so he would be around once in a while.
But Ty was...
He was a nice fellow, and he was very hospitable, very Texan.
He reminded me a lot.
Lyndon Johnson reminded me of Ty, the best parts of Lyndon Johnson.
You know, he'd almost embrace you.
And so I have fond memories of Ty.
I think he took pretty good care of you.
Did you and your colleagues have the impression that he was in charge?
Oh, yeah, yeah, no question about it in those times.
Ty was the head.
Within the school of agriculture, it would have been before the university, within the school of agriculture, what status did you all think we had among the department?
Well,

I never went to the library and checked the salaries of all these other departments to see who was doing better, but we were sort of the social science, we were the social science of agriculture, and not being a tech department is not always, I don't think you're always appreciated as much by other tech departments as a social science department.
So I'm not sure how others felt about him, but I think he did, given who he was and where he was and who he represented,
I thought he did a pretty good job.
Let me say this.
He liked for you to go through channels, because I remember the day that Snow White, who was a graduate student in the third floor restroom, I was in it.
There were four restrooms in the Ag building, one female restroom on the basement floor.
And this was in the mid to late 60s.
And Snow White and her friends came into this restroom and said, we're going to take this to the women.
And they did.
and eventually became a female rescue, but the tie was extremely because they didn't go through the channel.
They should have gone through .
As with much of A&M.
I remember that incident.
You mentioned salary comparison.
Where in that era could a person have found a faculty member
Well, when I got here, I don't think you could find it anywhere.
I don't know where you would have found it.
It wasn't, you know better than I, but I forget when it was.
And one time I did go to the library in the periodical room and look at the budget.
And I still had trouble figuring out.
In agriculture, because people were paid from two, maybe three sources.
what their actual compensation was.
But no, in the early days, unless somebody told you, you didn't know what.
I think the only place was at the state library.
Was it?
All right.
In those early years, you were paid from the teaching budget.
I got two checks.
Literally two different sections.
One from TA and C, and one from TAX.
But not the extension?
No, I wasn't interested.
Very few people, when I got here, I don't know anybody who had a three-way appointment.
There may have been other times.
Everybody was either teaching, most were teaching research, and then you were extension.
You weren't both.
Now, over time, some people began to carry a little bit of extension, and then some extension people began to carry teaching positions, joints.
And there may be some now that are all free, but they wouldn't be free.
I think Tom and I can be all free.
So, you know, early in the year, what would have been the average percentage?
One-third or one-third?
Yeah, as I recall, yeah.
And mostly, we mostly researched.
Speaking, we had, well, I forget how many courses we had.
I'd like to check, but most everybody just taught one or two courses.
When you, in the early years, when you got here and then two years after, describe as many as you have.
Vice President of University of Florida.
Gosh, you've caught me here because I know they're there.
I just can't.
Well, but what about some of these other longtime, Bob Branson, describe him.
Well, Bob came here.
Bob was a Harvard man, SMU at Harvard.
And Bob is a workaholic.
He is in marketing.
And he's always doing this.
He still is in his 80s working, doing surveys, working with savings and loans or real estate people.
Or at that time, he was working with marketing companies.
with firms, with grocery stores, with packers and shippers.
And Bob stayed here the whole time.
Bob was not all that big on publishing, at least in the journals, but he got a lot of reports out.
But he just loved to do those kind of studies.
He was an interesting individual.
And is still active, even though he's been retired, I guess, 10 years or more, maybe more.
McNeely, John McNeely was head of research
John was from North Dakota.
I remember he used to make the statement that a lot of good ag economists came out of North Dakota because people would do almost anything to get out of North Dakota.
But he's right.
There was a disproportionate number of noted agricultural economists came out of the Dakotas.
And John was the research head, and he published some.
He was in marketing.
But he stayed here the rest of his career.
Pat Wooten was graduate teaching.
I don't think Pat
I don't think Pat published much at all.
He just did the graduate teaching stuff and taught himself.
J.C. Grady came here from Missouri as head of the undergraduate section, and he was leader of that for years and taught.
Now, he was probably the closest thing we had to a full-time teacher.
Peter Berry came through here and is now a fellow in the association, but he's at Illinois.
A lot of, you know, I can't recall all these names.

Jim Hildreth came here from Illinois and quickly became associate director of the Experiment Station and then went to the Farm Foundation in Chicago, and he's been there ever since, retired some time back.
He was a well-known economist.
One of the names you mentioned a while ago, legendary, was this man Reagan Brown.
Reagan Brown, yes.
Scribe Reagan Brown.
Reagan Brown, I mean, he had the best stories.
I'm not sure what the content of Reagan's speeches were, but he was constant entertainment.
He was the most entertaining speaker I think I've ever heard as far as humor goes, and not second and patriotic either in terms of putting on a patriotic show.
Reagan was a rural sociologist, which was interesting that he would be in sociology because I think most people thought sociology was a bit of a liberal field.
But he was a real sociologist, probably may have had a master's degree, may have had a master's degree, I'm not sure.
But he was the ultimate Texan, very straight-laced, and could tell stories ad infinitum.
And a helpful guy, cordial.
And he was a good emcee, emceed lots of things around here.
You'll recall that Hal Brown emceed something Reagan was supposed to.
But he was legendary.
Was he helpful as a colleague?
Well, I never dealt with anything in rural sociology, so I didn't deal with him directly.
There was a rural sociology section within the sociology part of our department.
And then later, of course, sociology moved out.
But, yeah, if you wanted help,
But again, I think probably I suffered career-wise from not going to people, not knowing enough to go to people for help.
I just did my own thing.
But I never found anybody who wasn't helpful of the Texan-type staff.
Who became your closest departmental buddies in the 60s, in the early years?
Well, there was a guy named Jim Graves who's now at Texas Tech and is retired.
And that was partly because we were about the same age and our children were similar ages.
Jim was a buddy.
Rod Martin, who is a production economist.
It used to be, in the old days, when the government had more money, the federal government, that...
Lonnie Jones, who's still in our faculty, he's a little younger than I am, was a good friend.
He was in marketing at the time.
And our families were similar.
And that was in the early days.
Those guys and other, well, Russell Pops and Hal Brown, but Hal wasn't here at home.
And Russell wasn't here a whole lot longer.
Of the faculty that are close to Lonnie.
And that, I'm sure, means something else.
Of course, then I got to meet, fortunately, historians and other people whom we became good or better friends with.
And in those early years, what was your normal daily routine?
What time did you get to the office, lunch, and go to work?
Well, you needed to be at the office pretty close to 8 o'clock.
That was expected.
And you could take an hour for lunch, but you better be there...
Pretty much till 12 and start again at 1 and be there till 5.
In fact, there was a whistle.
There was a whistle on the water tower.
I remember the mill whistle when I was a kid growing up.
There was a row of mills in my home town.
It made honeydew flowers.
And there was a whistle.
It would blow at 8, it would blow at 12, it would blow at 1, it would blow at 5.
And it was the same thing here.
On the water tower, there was a big steam gun whistle.
Did you and other faculty members watch that whistle?
Well, being sophisticated intellectuals, we felt that was a bit mundane and beneath us to have to pay attention to the whistle, which we didn't.
But we were there from 8 to 12 and 1 to 5.
Do you remember if anybody ever heard of it?
Oh, yeah.
When I got here.
In those early years, did you and your colleagues take coffee breaks?
Yeah, we did.
There was a coffee room on the third floor of the building on the south end, and we did go meet frequently there.
It wasn't formal or anything, but then that was mostly the research teaching guys.
The extension guys would get in the car or cars and drive over to the Ramada Inn and drink their coffee.
Once in a while, we'd walk over to the MSC.
Of course, the campus wasn't crowded then.
There was no problem.
In fact, I don't remember even having a parking sticker when I first got here.
You just drove up and parked where you wanted to.
But yeah, there was more collegiality then in terms of coffee breaks than there are now.
In fact, we used to have a seminar.
I don't know if you remember this, but this was interdepartmental at the YMCA.
There was a seminar once a week, and
And some people talked about their discipline.
Some people talked about the sailboats.
I mean, Ed Doran over in meteorology talked about sailing.
Somebody else, I talked about carrots.
John Tracy talked about whatever he wanted to.
And that was a good thing.
But that wasn't a coffee break.
That was a seminar once a week.
And isn't that what we call the brown bag seminar?
Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, I thought it was.
How did you get back and forth from the campus?
Well, let's see.
I think I got a bicycle almost immediately, which was not unique.
But it was almost unique.
When we moved here, we lived on Nagel, about four blocks from the campus north in Bryan.
And so I got a 10-speed bicycle, ancient Schwinn, bought from somebody west of town.
And I rode that thing to work.
Because we only had one car.
And if you only had one car, then your wife couldn't go anywhere if you had the car at work.
So I rode the bike and have almost ever since.
Now, surely you had some interesting experiences in certain days of weather with your suit.
Well, yeah, you had to wear a raincoat.
Or if it was really bad, then I'd get Peggy to bring me to work.
But, yeah.
Yeah, you had to watch out for the weather.
It seems to me like, I may be wrong, it used to rain a lot more down here than it does now.
It was humid in the summer and the wintertime, but not.
And where was the parking lot for the agriculture building?
Right behind it.
I mean, you didn't have to spend much time going from your car to the building.
Describe the diversity of the faculty of the department.
You mean what I got here?
Mm-hmm.
Well, it wasn't real diverse.
I'm trying to think that... Now, of course, Ty had a degree from somewhere else.
The Head did, and Branson did, and I imagine McNeely did.
He probably from North Dakota.
But most people had their degrees from Texas A&M.
It was not real diverse.
What about their ethnic diversity?
Oh, all-white male, period.
I mean, that was all-white male...
Now, Stelly was a Cajun.
Randall Stelly from Louisiana.
What was his specialty?
He was milk marketing.
He was a dairy marketing specialist.
And were there any internationally born?
Internationally born?
No.
Somebody from outside the U.S.?
No.
They were all U.S. nationals from birth?
And as far as you can recall, all U.S. degrees?
Yes.
And about how many, what was the percentage of PhDs, you reckon?
Well, it would be low.
No, no, not nearly that high.
No, I would say maybe.
Of course, the question, well, how do you figure the faculty?
Do you figure the extension guys in there or what?
But of the whole, what we would consider when we had a faculty meeting, which would include the extension people, I would think not more than a fourth.
at that time, if that many.
In a departmental discussion, was there any obvious difference in the prestige clout of those that were extension primarily compared with those that were teaching and research?
Well, in fact, I don't think so.
We may have thought so because we had degrees, but
The extension guys were the older, been in the Hornets longer, probably had more pull than did the younger so-called degreed faculty at that time.
But, you know, people in research teaching probably thought they were more important than extension and vice versa.
But I didn't notice any, there's always been a little,
what do you call it, between Extension and the research teaching people.
I think it's gotten less over the years because we've gotten more joint appointments.
But the Extension guys thought they were doing more applied, more practical work than the research teachers.
In those early days, do you remember any big departmental decision that there was a lot of pulling and tugging on and how it finally came out?
Oh, well, we had some big departmental studies, but I don't recall, you know, I probably will when you leave, but anything of momentous, like name change wasn't an issue then.
Now, today, it's name change.
What should we change our name to?
Not then, that wasn't a problem.
I don't know how the decision was made to separate sociology from agricultural economics.
never entered my realm.
So offhand, no, I don't.
What was the departmental reaction to the campus decision to admit women and non-compulsory core and racial integration and broaden the curriculum and change the name of the institution?
Well, I think that most of it was welcomed.
I think we were
quote, academic enough that we identified with the needs to do that.
And I'm not sure if you talk to the old timers.
Like, I don't know what Reagan's position.
It'd be interesting to know what Reagan's position would have been on that, Reagan Brown.
But I think they almost realized the necessity, if this place was going to stay in business, as sort of like President Rudder presented it, that we had to do that.
And welcoming...
Yeah, I think most of them welcomed it.
You'll remember the aspiration study of 62, which some of us actually read.
I think most of the faculty were fairly progressive on that.
When we got our first faculty female, we were not as supportive of her as we should, and the old dip in
redneck cowboy contingent of the student body, I think almost literally ran her off.
She was just not accepted.
About when was that, do you know?
Oh, I'm trying to, I really, I remember her name was Judy, and I can't think of Judy's last name.
That had to be, what, early 70s, late 60s, or maybe early 70s.
How long was she here?
Not long, two, three years.
Yeah, not long.
And she was teaching one of the toughest courses, too.
So I don't think that was done on purpose.
But she just, well, there were some yahoos in there.
And as I recall, that was a rumor that she just couldn't take it.
And I can believe that.
You mean these were students?
Students, yeah, students.
Not the faculty, but students.
How did the faculty treat her?
Well, as I recall, she was treated okay.
I mean, I don't remember any disparaging behavior.
Did she, as far as you know, did she complain about the way the department treated her ever?
Well, not to me.
I mean, I didn't hear it.
She may have, who knows?
I don't know.
Not that I know of.
It's been a long time.
All right, let's go back.
In your first, the first courses that you teach, what was your impression of Aggie students?
Well, you know, relative to what?
Because I hadn't taught.
I had been an instructor to a little extent at Penn State.
And my impression of students were they were mostly core at that time.
They were respectful, courteous, not necessarily all valedictorians, but they were well-behaved.
And at that time, of course, most of them were well-dressed and well-kempt.
It wasn't the Vietnam thing had not come along then.
Not that that mattered much at this point down here.
But easy to deal with, not close to the faculty in the sense of none of the buddy-buddy stuff, you know.
They pretty well...
